A binary tree is a tree data structure in which each node has at most two children, referred to as the left child and the right child. The left child is generally smaller than the parent, while the right child is generally larger than the parent, though this is not a strict requirement.

A binary tree can be represented in memory using a linked data structure. Each node in the tree is represented as an object or a struct that contains three fields: a data field to store the node's value, and two pointers to its left and right children.

Here's an example of how to represent a binary tree using a linked data structure in C++:
```scss
struct TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode* left;
    TreeNode* right;
    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(NULL), right(NULL) {}
};

// Sample binary tree:        1
//                         /   \
//                        2     3
//                       / \   / \
//                      4   5 6   7

// Create the root node
TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(1);

// Create the left and right child nodes of the root
root->left = new TreeNode(2);
root->right = new TreeNode(3);

// Create the left and right child nodes of the left child
root->left->left = new TreeNode(4);
root->left->right = new TreeNode(5);

// Create the left and right child nodes of the right child
root->right->left = new TreeNode(6);
root->right->right = new TreeNode(7);
```
In this example, we have created a binary tree with 7 nodes. The root of the tree is represented by a TreeNode object with a value of 1. Its left child has a value of 2 and its right child has a value of 3. The left child of the root has two children with values 4 and 5, while the right child of the root has two children with values 6 and 7.

This is just one example of how to represent a binary tree using a linked data structure. There are other ways to represent binary trees, such as using an array or a matrix, but the linked data structure is the most common and intuitive way to represent them.

Sure, here's an example pipe that converts a date/time value to a specific timezone and outputs the server UTC Z format:
```typescript
import { Pipe, PipeTransform } from '@angular/core';

@Pipe({
  name: 'timezone'
})
export class TimezonePipe implements PipeTransform {

  transform(value: any, timezone: string): any {
    const date = new Date(value);
    const timezoneOffset = date.getTimezoneOffset() / 60;
    const localTimezoneOffset = (new Date().getTimezoneOffset()) / 60;
    const utcTimezoneOffset = timezoneOffset + localTimezoneOffset;
    const timezoneHours = parseInt(timezone.slice(0, 3), 10);
    const timezoneMinutes = parseInt(timezone.slice(3), 10);
    const offsetHours = timezoneHours - utcTimezoneOffset;
    const offsetMinutes = timezoneMinutes - date.getTimezoneOffset() % 60;
    const offsetSign = offsetHours > 0 ? '+' : '-';
    const offsetHoursAbs = Math.abs(offsetHours).toString().padStart(2, '0');
    const offsetMinutesAbs = Math.abs(offsetMinutes).toString().padStart(2, '0');
    const offset = `${offsetSign}${offsetHoursAbs}${offsetMinutesAbs}`;

    return date.toLocaleString('en-US', { timeZone: timezone }) + ' (' + offset + ')';
  }
}
```
In this example, the `timezone` pipe takes two arguments: the value to be transformed (a date/time string in ISO format) and the target timezone (a string representing the timezone offset in hours and minutes, such as `"-0500"` for Eastern Standard Time in the United States).

The pipe calculates the offset between the server's UTC time and the target timezone, and then formats the date/time value according to the target timezone. It also generates the server UTC Z format by calculating the offset from UTC and formatting it as `"+HHMM"` or `"-HHMM"`.

You can use this pipe in your templates like this:
```html
<p>{{ myDate | timezone: '-0500' }}</p>
```
This would output the date/time value in the Eastern Standard Time timezone, along with the server UTC Z format for that timezone.

