Here's a complete program that includes both an inline assembly version of `wrap_angle()` for Cortex-M7 and a portable C++ version without library function calls. The preprocessor is used to select the appropriate implementation based on the target architecture:
```cpp
#include <iostream>

const float two_pi = 2.0f * M_PI;
const float one_over_two_pi = 1.0f / two_pi;

#ifdef __ARM_ARCH_7EM__

float wrap_angle(float angle) {
    float result;

    __asm__ __volatile__(
        "vmul.f32 s1, s0, %2\n\t"      // Multiply angle by one_over_two_pi (s1 = angle * one_over_two_pi)
        "vcvt.s32.f32 s1, s1\n\t"      // Convert s1 to a signed integer
        "vcvt.f32.s32 s1, s1\n\t"      // Convert the integer value back to a float
        "vmul.f32 s1, s1, %3\n\t"      // Multiply s1 by two_pi (s1 = floor(angle * one_over_two_pi) * two_pi)
        "vsub.f32 %0, s0, s1\n\t"      // Subtract s1 from angle (result = angle - s1)
        : "=t"(result)                 // Output operand
        : "t"(angle), "t"(one_over_two_pi), "t"(two_pi)  // Input operands
        : "s1"                          // Clobbered register
    );

    return result;
}

#else

float wrap_angle(float angle) {
    float wrapped = angle * one_over_two_pi;
    wrapped -= static_cast<int>(wrapped);
    wrapped *= two_pi;
    return wrapped;
}

#endif

int main() {
    float test_angles[] = {0.0f, M_PI, -M_PI, 3 * M_PI, -3 * M_PI, 5 * M_PI, -5 * M_PI};

    for (float angle : test_angles) {
        float wrapped_angle = wrap_angle(angle);
        std::cout << "Input angle: " << angle << ", wrapped angle: " << wrapped_angle << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This program first checks if the target architecture is Cortex-M7 (`__ARM_ARCH_7EM__`). If it is, the program uses the inline assembly version of `wrap_angle()`. Otherwise, it uses the portable C++ version without library function calls. The `main()` function tests the `wrap_angle()` function with some interesting input angles and prints the results.

Please note that this example assumes the compiler supports the `__ARM_ARCH_7EM__` macro for the Cortex-M7 architecture. The exact macro name might differ depending on the compiler being used. Make sure to adapt the macro accordingly.

