\begin{align\*}
z\_j &= w x\_j + u h\_{j-1} \
h\_j &= f(z\_j)
\end{align\*}

Using the chain rule, we can compute the derivative of $h\_m$ with respect to $h\_1$ as follows:

\begin{align\*}
\frac{d h\_m}{d h\_1} &= \frac{d h\_m}{d z\_m} \frac{d z\_m}{d h\_{m-1}} \cdots \frac{d z\_3}{d h\_2} \frac{d z\_2}{d h\_1} \
&= f'(z\_m) u f'(z\_{m-1}) \cdots u f'(z\_2) f'(z\_1) \
&= \prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} (u f'(z\_j))
\end{align\*}

Note that the product depends on the intermediate pre-activation values $z\_j$, which in turn depend on the input sequence $\mathbf{x}$. In the case where the absolute value of $\prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} (u f'(z\_j))$ is small, we have a vanishing gradient problem, and in the case where it is large, we have an exploding gradient problem.

