Sure, here are the general steps to set up the Gmail API and obtain authentication and authorization:

1. Create a project in the Google Cloud Console: Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/), create a new project, and enable the Gmail API for that project.
2. Set up authentication credentials: In the Google Cloud Console, go to the "Credentials" section and create a new OAuth 2.0 client ID. You will need to specify the "Application type" as "Chrome app", the "Authorized JavaScript origins" as `chrome-extension://[your-extension-id]`, and the "Authorized redirect URIs" as `chrome-extension://[your-extension-id]/oauth2callback`. Note that you will need to replace `[your-extension-id]` with your actual extension ID.
3. Add the Gmail API library to your extension: In your extension's manifest file, add the following line to the "background" section: `"oauth2": {"client_id": "YOUR_CLIENT_ID_HERE", "scopes": ["https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly"]}`. Note that you will need to replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID_HERE` with the client ID you obtained in step 2.
4. Handle authentication and authorization in your extension: In your background script, add the following code to handle the authentication and authorization process:
```javascript
// Load the OAuth2 library
chrome.identity.getAuthToken({ 'interactive': true }, function(token) {
  // Use the token to authenticate with the Gmail API
  gapi.auth.setToken({ 'access_token': token });
});

// Authorize the user to access their Gmail account
function authorize(callback) {
  gapi.auth.authorize({
    'client_id': 'YOUR_CLIENT_ID_HERE',
    'scope': 'https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly',
    'immediate': false
  }, callback);
}

// Initialize the Gmail API client
function initApiClient(callback) {
  gapi.client.load('gmail', 'v1', callback);
}
```
This code uses the Chrome Identity API to authenticate the user and obtain an OAuth2 token, which is then used to authorize access to the Gmail API. The `authorize` function prompts the user to grant permission to the extension to access their Gmail account, and the `initApiClient` function initializes the Gmail API client.

Note that the `interactive` parameter is set to `true` in the `getAuthToken` call, which means that the user will be prompted to grant permission to the extension. If you want to avoid this prompt and use a pre-authorized token instead, you can set `interactive` to `false` and use the `chrome.storage` API to store and retrieve the token.

