Sure! Here's an example of how to use `http.NewRequest` to verify a reCAPTCHA token instead of `http.Post`:
```go
func verifyRecaptchaV3(token string, secretKey string, remoteIP string) (*RecaptchaResponse, error) {
	recaptchaURL := "https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api/siteverify"
	form := url.Values{}
	form.Add("secret", secretKey)
	form.Add("response", token)
	form.Add("remoteip", remoteIP)
	req, err := http.NewRequest("POST", recaptchaURL, bytes.NewBufferString(form.Encode()))
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	req.Header.Add("Content-Type", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded")
	client := &http.Client{}
	resp, err := client.Do(req)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	defer resp.Body.Close()
	var recaptchaResponse RecaptchaResponse
	err = json.NewDecoder(resp.Body).Decode(&recaptchaResponse)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	if len(recaptchaResponse.ErrorCodes) != 0 {
		return nil, errors.New("reCAPTCHA error: " + strings.Join(recaptchaResponse.ErrorCodes, ", "))
	}
	return &recaptchaResponse, nil
}
```
In this example, `http.NewRequest` is used to create an `http.Request` struct. The request has a "POST" method, and it is sent to the URL `"https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api/siteverify"`. The body of the request contains the reCAPTCHA token, the secret key, and the client's IP address, encoded as a `x-www-form-urlencoded` in the request body.

The `http.Client.Do` method is used to send the request to the server, and the response is read and decoded from the body of the response.

This approach allows you to have more control over the http request, for example if you need to set more headers or custom timeout.

