Here is the Mermaid diagram representing the category, functor, and natural transformation for the double entry accounting system to manage student fees for school enrollment:
```mermaid
    %% Category
    graph TD;
      A(FeeType) -->|has| B(Fee);
      B -->|charged for| C(Student);
      C -->|enrolls in| D(SchoolYear);
      D -->|consists of| E(Term);
      E -->|contains| F(PaymentSchedule);
      F -->|makes| G(Payment);
      G -->|belongs to| H(AccountingPeriod);
      H -->|manages| I(Ledger);
      J(DiscountType) -->|gives| B;

    %% Functor
    subgraph "F";
      A1(FeeType') -->|has| B1(Fee');
      B1 -->|charged for| C1(Student');
      C1 -->|enrolls in| D1(SchoolYear');
      D1 -->|consists of| E1(Term');
      E1 -->|contains| F1(PaymentSchedule');
      F1 -->|makes| G1(Payment');
      G1 -->|belongs to| H1(AccountingPeriod');
      H1 -->|manages| I1(Ledger');
      J1(DiscountType') -->|gives| B1;
    end

    %% Natural Transformation
    A -- sameAs --> A1;
    B -- sameAs --> B1;
    C -- sameAs --> C1;
    D -- sameAs --> D1;
    E -- sameAs --> E1;
    F -- sameAs --> F1;
    G -- sameAs --> G1;
    H -- sameAs --> H1;
    I -- sameAs --> I1;
    J -- sameAs --> J1;
```
In the above diagram, `FeeType`, `Fee`, `Student`, `SchoolYear`, `Term`, `PaymentSchedule`, `Payment`, `AccountingPeriod`, `Ledger`, and `DiscountType` represent the objects in our category. `FeeType` has a relationship "has" with `Fee`, which is "charged for" `Student`. `Student` "enrolls in" `SchoolYear`, which "consists of" `Term`. `Term` "contains" `PaymentSchedule`, which "makes" `Payment`. `Payment` "belongs to" `AccountingPeriod`, which "manages" `Ledger`. Finally, `DiscountType` "gives" `Fee`.

The subgraph "F" represents the functor, with the same objects as the category but with a prime symbol, e.g., `FeeType'`, `Fee'`, `Student'`, and so on. The natural transformation connects the objects in the category with their counterparts in the functor using the "sameAs" relationship.

