To add Netlify Identity authentication to your website, you can follow these steps:

1. Enable Identity on your Netlify site: In your Netlify dashboard, go to the "Identity" tab and click on "Enable Identity". This will create a new Identity instance for your site.
2. Add the Netlify Identity widget to your site: You can add the Netlify Identity widget to your site by including the following JavaScript code in your HTML:
```html
<script src="https://identity.netlify.com/v1/netlify-identity-widget.js"></script>
```
1. Create a login button: You can create a login button by adding the following HTML code to your page:
```html
<button onclick="openLoginModal()">Log in</button>
```
1. Open the login modal: When the user clicks on the login button, you can open the login modal by calling the `netlifyIdentity.open()` function. Here's an example:
```js
function openLoginModal() {
  netlifyIdentity.open();
}
```
1. Listen for authentication events: You can listen for authentication events using the `netlifyIdentity.on()` function. For example, you can listen for the `login` event to update the UI when the user logs in:
```js
netlifyIdentity.on('login', user => {
  console.log('Logged in', user);
  // Update the UI to show that the user is logged in
});
```
1. Protect your endpoints: To protect your endpoints with Netlify Identity, you can add the `JWT` header to your requests. This header contains the user's access token, which can be used to verify the user's identity. Here's an example of how you can protect your `/convert` endpoint:
```js
app.post('/convert', async (req, res) => {
  const accessToken = req.headers.authorization.replace('Bearer ', '');
  const { user } = await netlifyIdentity.gotrue.getUserByAccessToken(accessToken);
  if (!user) {
    res.status(401).send({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
    return;
  }

  const userId = user.id;
  const names = req.body.names;
  const nameFormat = req.body.nameFormat;
  const convertedNames = nameConverter.convertNames(names, nameFormat);

  // Store the conversion in the database
  const client = await pool.connect();
  try {
    await client.query('INSERT INTO conversions (user_id, names, name_format, converted_names) VALUES ($1, $2, $3, $4)', [userId, names, nameFormat, convertedNames]);
  } finally {
    client.release();
  }

  res.send(convertedNames);
});
```
In this example, we're extracting the access token from the `Authorization` header, using the `netlifyIdentity.gotrue.getUserByAccessToken()` function to verify the user's identity, and returning a 401 response if the user is not authenticated. If the user is authenticated, we're proceeding with the conversion and storing the result in the database as before.

These are just some general steps to get you started with Netlify Identity authentication. For more information and advanced configuration options, you can refer to the Netlify Identity documentation.

