Sure! In React Native, you can break down your application into reusable components. Each component is like a building block that can be used to build your application UI.

Here's an example of how you can organize your code:

1. Create a `components` folder for all your reusable components.
2. Create a `screens` folder for each screen in your application. Each screen will have its own folder with an `index.js` file.
3. Create a `services` folder for all the logic that communicates with the backend server or any external services.
4. Create a `utils` folder for any utility functions or helpers that can be reused throughout the application.

To connect these modules, you can use a navigation library such as React Navigation. React Navigation provides different types of navigators such as Stack Navigator, Drawer Navigator, and Tab Navigator to help you navigate between different screens.

Here's an example of how you can use React Navigation to navigate between screens:

1. In your `App.js` file, import the necessary screens and create a stack navigator.
```javascript
import { createStackNavigator } from '@react-navigation/stack';
import HomeScreen from './screens/HomeScreen';
import ProfileScreen from './screens/ProfileScreen';

const Stack = createStackNavigator();

function App() {
  return (
    <NavigationContainer>
      <Stack.Navigator>
        <Stack.Screen name="Home" component={HomeScreen} />
        <Stack.Screen name="Profile" component={ProfileScreen} />
      </Stack.Navigator>
    </NavigationContainer>
  );
}

export default App;
```
1. In your `HomeScreen.js` file, create a button that navigates to the `ProfileScreen`.
```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { Button, View } from 'react-native';

function HomeScreen({ navigation }) {
  return (
    <View>
      <Button
        title="Go to Profile"
        onPress={() => navigation.navigate('Profile')}
      />
    </View>
  );
}

export default HomeScreen;
```
1. In your `ProfileScreen.js` file, create a button that navigates back to the `HomeScreen`.
```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { Button, View } from 'react-native';

function ProfileScreen({ navigation }) {
  return (
    <View>
      <Button
        title="Go back to Home"
        onPress={() => navigation.goBack()}
      />
    </View>
  );
}

export default ProfileScreen;
```
With this basic setup, you can navigate between screens in your application. You can add more screens and more complex navigations as needed.

Sure, you can add the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header to your HTTP responses to enable CORS on your server. This header tells the browser which origins are allowed to access your server's resources.

To add the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header to your server's responses, you will need to modify your server-side code. The exact method for doing this will depend on the language and framework you are using for your server. Here's an example of how you can add this header using Node.js and Express:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  // Set the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header to allow requests from all origins
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*');

  // Set the Access-Control-Allow-Methods header to allow GET and POST requests
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, POST');

  // Set the Access-Control-Allow-Headers header to allow the Content-Type header
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');

  // Call the next middleware function
  next();
});

// Add your routes and other middleware here
```
This middleware function will add the necessary headers to enable CORS for all incoming requests. You can modify the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header to allow requests from specific origins, if needed.

