I apologize for the inconvenience. It seems that the `sequelize-cli` doesn't support TypeScript configuration files out of the box. One solution is to create a JavaScript version of the configuration file, and import the TypeScript configuration from it.

First, create a new file named `database.config.js` in the same folder where your `database.config.ts` file is located (`libs/database/src/config/`). Then, add the following content to the new file:
```javascript
require('ts-node/register');
const config = require('./database.config.ts');

module.exports = config;
```
Next, update your `.sequelizerc` file to reference the new JavaScript configuration file:
```javascript
const path = require('path');

module.exports = {
  'config': path.resolve('libs', 'database', 'src', 'config', 'database.config.js'),
  'migrations-path': path.resolve('libs', 'database', 'src', 'migrations'),
  'models-path': path.resolve('libs', 'database', 'src', 'models')
};
```
Now you should be able to run your migrations without any issues:
```bash
npm run db:migrate
```
This approach allows you to keep using your TypeScript configuration while also making it compatible with `sequelize-cli`.

In C++, a namespace is a container that holds a set of identifiers (e.g. variable names, function names, etc.). Namespaces are used to organize the code and to prevent naming conflicts between different parts of the code. A namespace allows you to use the same identifier in different parts of the code without creating a naming collision.

A namespace is defined by the keyword "namespace" followed by the namespace name and a block of code. Identifiers that are declared inside a namespace are only accessible from within the namespace. To access an identifier from outside the namespace, you need to use the scope resolution operator (::) to specify the namespace name.

Here is an example of a simple namespace:
```
#include <iostream>

namespace my_namespace {
    int my_var = 5;
    void my_func() {
        std::cout << "Hello from my_namespace" << std::endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    std::cout << my_namespace::my_var << std::endl;
    my_namespace::my_func();
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the namespace "my\_namespace" contains an integer variable "my\_var" and a function "my\_func". To access these identifiers from outside the namespace, you need to use the scope resolution operator (::) to specify the namespace name.

It's worth noting that the "std" namespace is the most commonly used namespace in C++, which contains the standard library functions, classes, and objects. To use the standard library, you have to include the appropriate headers and use the std namespace.

