If you are looking for a simpler design pattern for your habit tracking app, one option could be the model-view-presenter (MVP) pattern.

The MVP pattern is a variation of the model-view-controller (MVC) pattern that focuses on separating the presentation logic from the business logic and the data model. It does this by introducing a presenter component that handles the presentation logic and communicates with the model and the view.

Here is an example of how the MVP pattern could be applied to a habit tracking app:
```
class HabitModel {
  final String description;
  final int frequency;
  final String notes;
  int progress;
  final DateTime started;
  final DateTime goalTime;
  int totalPerformed;
  double successRate;

  HabitModel({
    this.description,
    this.frequency,
    this.notes,
    this.progress,
    this.started,
    this.goalTime,
    this.totalPerformed,
    this.successRate,
  });
}

abstract class HabitView {
  void displayHabit(HabitModel habit);
  void displayError(String errorMessage);
}

class HabitPresenter {
  HabitView _view;
  HabitModel _model;

  HabitPresenter(this._view, this._model);

  void updateProgress(int newProgress) {
    _model.progress = newProgress;
    _view.displayHabit(_model);
  }

  void updateTotalPerformed(int newTotalPerformed) {
    _model.totalPerformed = newTotalPerformed;
    _view.displayHabit(_model);
  }

  void updateSuccessRate() {
    _model.successRate = _calculateSuccessRate();
    _view.displayHabit(_model);
  }

  double _calculateSuccessRate() {
    // ...
  }
}
```
