You can map the error returned from the Supabase client to your custom error by creating a new instance of your custom error class and passing the relevant information from the Supabase error as arguments to the constructor. Here's an example implementation:
```typescript
class MyAppError extends Error {
  status: number;
  source: string;

  constructor(status: number, message: string, source: string) {
    super(message);
    this.status = status;
    this.source = source;
  }
}

async function fetchData() {
  const { data, error } = await supabase.from('mytable').select();

  if (error) {
    const myAppError = new MyAppError(error.status, error.message, 'Supabase');
    handleCustomError(myAppError);
    throw myAppError;
  }

  return data;
}
```
In the above example, if the Supabase client returns an error, we create a new instance of `MyAppError` and pass the relevant information from the Supabase error (`error.status`, `error.message`, and `'Supabase'` as the `source`). We then pass this custom error instance to our `handleCustomError` function, and finally throw the custom error so it can be caught and handled appropriately elsewhere in the code.
